Create a server-only singleton `JazzContext` at process startup/module scope, not per request:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency for Node.js. Use a stable `dataPath` for durable local state; `{ type: "memory" }` is ephemeral and should only be used with an upstream `serverUrl`. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never expose them through public framework env vars. Reuse the context across requests, call `await jazz.shutdown()` during process shutdown, and explicitly wait for the needed durability tier before returning success from endpoints that promise persisted or server-visible writes.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional Jazz column. `undefined` means “leave unchanged” in partial updates.

```ts
await db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

If the caller does not need sync confirmation, keep the local-first optimistic write and omit `.wait(...)`.

For Svelte and Solid, pass an accessor/function so Jazz can rebuild the query when reactive inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  selectedProjectId
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
);
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: selectedProjectId()
    ? app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc")
    : undefined,
}));
```

Do not pass a prebuilt query when its inputs are reactive; that captures the current value instead of tracking later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for the two optimistic UI writes. A batch makes the writes become locally visible together after the callback commits, then they settle as one direct batch.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` for two writes that must remain staged until authority accepts them and then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});

await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Do not await individual writes inside the open batch or transaction; await the returned result.

Upload with an explicit edge write tier, then only create the parent after the file helper has settled there:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label,
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download, request the required tier and distinguish missing visibility from incomplete chunks:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return blob;
} catch (err) {
  if (err instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    return { state: "missing" };
  }
  if (err instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    return { state: "incomplete", reason: err.reason };
  }
  throw err;
}
```

Treat `IncompleteFileDataError` as a retry/repair state, not as “file not found”; reasons include invalid metadata, missing part, or part-size mismatch.

Keep the parent row until file cleanup is finished, because delete permissions are inherited through that relationship. Load the upload, load the referenced file, delete every part, delete the file row, then delete the upload:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete `uploads` first; doing so can remove the inherited authorization needed to delete `files` and `file_parts`, leaving orphaned chunks.

Use `counter` for the integer only if the column is a non-nullable integer and concurrent updates represent independent deltas from a shared ancestor.

```ts
const schema = {
  stats: s.table({
    count: s.int().default(0).merge("counter"),
  }),
  documents: s.table({
    tags: s.array(s.string()).default([]).merge("g-set"),
  }),
};
```

For `counter`, writers still write snapshots, for example `count: row.count + 1`. On a genuine concurrent frontier, Jazz compares each tip to the common ancestor, sums the deltas, and applies that to the ancestor. If the ancestor is `10` and concurrent tips are `12` and `9`, the converged value is `11`.

Use `g-set` for tags only if concurrent additions should converge to a deduplicated union. Treat order as canonical/storage order, not display order; sort separately in UI if needed. Important limitation: `g-set` only affects concurrent frontier resolution. A later sequential write can still replace the array and remove tags, so if removal must be impossible or you need authorship/audit/deduplication by operation ID, model tag additions as append-only operation rows instead.

Render from local-first state, but track confirmation separately from the displayed value.

Use an immediate local subscription/query for the editable document so keystrokes render without waiting for the network. When saving, keep the mutation handle returned by `db.update(...)` and wait for the appropriate settlement tier:

```ts
const write = db.update(app.documents, id, patch);
setSaveState("pending");

void write.wait({ tier: "edge" }).then(
  () => setSaveState("confirmed"),
  (error) => setSaveState({ kind: "rejected", error }),
);
```

For reads, keep collaborative data at `propagation: "full"`. Use `localUpdates: "immediate"` for the optimistic rendered value. If the UI also needs a last-confirmed version, maintain it from tracked write settlement or a separate `tier: "edge"`, `localUpdates: "deferred"` read. The write handle is usually clearer because identical values can have different settlement states.

On disconnect, local edits should remain visible and edge/global waits should stay pending. Show an offline/pending state instead of marking the edit saved. Register `db.onMutationError(...)` for un-awaited or restart-surviving failures, and on reconnect verify both directions: offline writes upload, and missed remote writes are retrieved. If duplicate non-idempotent intent is unacceptable after reconnect, use stable operation IDs and idempotent operation rows rather than relying on transport exactly-once behavior.

Use a real local sync topology and make the assertion order-independent. Create two memory clients against `startLocalJazzServer`, deploy schema if policies matter, have Alice insert several rows and await `.wait({ tier: "edge" })` for each or for the batch boundary. On Bob, use `vi.waitFor` and query at `tier: "edge"`. If row order is not behavior under test, either add explicit `orderBy` on a stable field or normalize before asserting:

```ts
await Promise.all([
  alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "b", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
  alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "a", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
  alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "c", done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
]);

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  expect(rows.map((r) => r.title).sort()).toEqual(["a", "b", "c"]);
});
```

Avoid fixed sleeps and avoid asserting raw query array order unless the query explicitly orders rows.

Use `createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect)` because this is row-policy behavior. Test Bob’s denied read as an empty result and Bob’s denied write as a rejected/denied mutation. Also assert Alice can access her own row so the test proves the policy boundary rather than broken setup.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob reads and writes to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
  const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

  const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private", done: false }).value;

  await expect(alice.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toHaveLength(1);
  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

  alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Alice edit" }));
  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Bob edit" }));
});
```

If the policy also controls delete or insert, add separate assertions for those operations; denied reads should be asserted as filtered rows, not exceptions.
